As some others have noted, game starts out fun and easy. I beat all the "easy" mode games on the first try. I beat the first "normal" mode game on two tries. Then the second normal mode game was seemingly impossible for me. Some people have said that the AI gets smarter after each win or loss, so if you surrender a game it still causes the AI to ratchet up the difficulty. The normal game that I kept losing the AI had mined 4-5x more minerals than me even though I controlled 3 mineral fields and had 5 refineries. They had an almost endless stream of mechs attacking my main base, there was no way I could counter. Also, one of their mechs could take out 2 of mine. I did have upgraded units and a mix of mechs, it didn't matter, they barreled right through my turrets even when assisted by my mechs and they kept coming faster than I could repair or build more mechs. I've played StarCraft and Warcraft without issue, but either I am missing something or this game's difficulty is too high for the average user.

There's no way to repair or sell buildings. While there are different weapon and chasis types for the mechs, they don't really have any difference-they just increase the armor and damage, and decrease the movement speed. There aren't any counters-for example lasers aren't stronger against a particular type of chasis, they just do more damage overall. A suggestion: add different armor types as an aditional item for the player to pick when building units. For example "Heavy" armor would be good against gatling and cannons, but weak vs lasers and rockets and vice versa. Also stealth and detection units would be awesome. And height-dependent fog of war(if units are lower, they shouldn't be able to see or shoot above cliffs)

Best depth of gameplay out of all three of these games. The devs have clearly put a lot of effort (and probably money) into this version. The maps are bigger and more interesting, the factions have differences to choose between, there is a research tree. In general it is very polished. My only gripe is that the 'select all' double tap doesn't pick up a group of units if there is even a tiny gap between them, but this is a minor issue. I have yet to really test the AI, particularly on the highest setting, but I would say this game will give you lots of bang for your buck and several years of play.

Not a bad game just so hard you will likely only get half way through.  It would feel fairer if you could make money from selling buildings like previous versions.  I was able to complete the second one and that seemed more balanced, but probably easily fixed by allowing you to sell buildings.

Great game for the price.  I've played all three mech coms and I think the potential is there for a great game.  AI is definitely improved from the last game and the AI will straight  up murder you if you don't scout and prepare  for attacks.   I do like how you have more choices about where to place buildings and the attempt to make the races unique (at least aesthetically), but I still think feel most units are too similar.  Slight differences in attack range, unit speed, and health are not enough to make the gameplay interesting.  Maybe adding stealth units, detection, aoe, and even assign in different supply costs to units might make things interesting.  In terms of the game economy, i like to play a high economy playstyle like in SC, and the limit of 3 structures building at one time prevents that.  Maybe for the next game just remove the limit or increase this number of structures you can build at one time?  Also I would like to have some sort of spellcaster ability or hero u nit, as there currently is no incentive to do anything but Zerg the opponent.  Also I feel that the turrets are weak, even when placing many of them.  Maybe add some sort of upgrade to them or have different types of turrets.  Then you can add some sort of siege units to take them down.  Would make the gameplay more fun and varied.

I have a few questions:  Who are the orange robots? How do they work?  How much do armory upgrades increase weapon damage and armor? Are there exact numbers?  Lightning seems to be better than Plasma and Laser in every way. Even their range is the same. Is there anything where blue is weaker than green and red?
replyContent:
Hello Kevin,

Thank you for your feedback!

The orange robots are pirates. They are landing in random places and hunting after harvesters. Armory increases params on 10% with each level. Lightnings has more damage but lowest range. All depends from your style of play, H.Wheels + Plasa with good microcontroller could be more stronger than Lightings.
